cs.ET, cs.AR, cs.NE, cs.DS, cs.CC

The paper discusses a novel non-Turing paradigm of computation that uses interacting memory cells to store and process information on the same physical platform. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Emerging Technologies (cs.ET) category. The paper also mentions the use of microelectronic technology, which could place it in the Architecture (cs.AR) category. The paper deals with solving NP-complete problems, which could suggest it belongs to the Complexity Theory (cs.CC) category. The paper also mentions intrinsic parallelism and information overhead, which could place it in the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) category. Finally, the paper discusses an experimental demonstration of an actual memcomputing architecture, which could suggest it belongs to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) category.
